---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="About — Matt Sanford" screenLabel="02 About" active="about">
  <section class="pagehead">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
      <h1>A math teacher who learned the body the hard way.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The classroom moved outside. The proofs got physical. The students
        started carrying packs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container" style="display:grid;grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.3fr; gap: 80px; align-items:start;">
      <div>
        <div
          class="photo-frame tall"
          style="background-image: url('/matt-portrait.jpg'); background-position: center top;"
        >
          <div class="label">On the marsh — North Shore</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          I'd been a high school math teacher for six years. I liked the
          work. I liked the quiet ratio of explanation to silence — say it
          once cleanly, let it sit, watch the room work it out. Then in 2009
          my body started doing things math couldn't account for. Thirst
          that didn't quit. Twenty pounds gone in a month. The diagnosis
          came on a Tuesday. Type 1 Diabetes. Autoimmune. Permanent.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the first year I learned a new language. Carb ratios. Basal
          rates. The lag between an injection and a meal. The way a single
          beer can take twelve hours to settle. I read endocrinology papers
          the way I used to read proofs — looking for the line that ties
          everything together.
        </p>
        <p>The line, it turned out, was movement.</p>
        <p>
          Exercise is the most powerful single intervention I have on this
          disease. A walk after lunch is worth more than most of the tools
          in my insulin kit. A heavy lift on a Tuesday writes glucose
          dynamics into Wednesday and Thursday. The body that used to feel
          like a problem started behaving more like a solution.
        </p>
        <h2>From the classroom to the gym floor</h2>
        <p>
          I started studying the way I'd studied everything else — slowly,
          completely, and with a bias toward people who knew more than I
          did. I trained at a small strength gym on the North Shore for
          years before I ever coached anyone. When I started looking for a
          certification, I wanted one that took the whole body seriously. I
          found the CHEK Institute.
        </p>
        <p>
          CHEK is not a weekend cert. It's a thirty-year holistic system
          that treats movement, recovery, mind, and life as the same
          problem. The first thing they teach you is that the brain
          prioritizes survival systems in a specific order, and if you
          train against that order you waste your client's time. The squat
          is not where you start.
        </p>
        <p>
          I started where they tell you to start: with breath, with
          posture, with the parts of the body that quietly run everything
          else. And then, because I'd been a teacher, I started translating
          the system into language a smart adult can actually use.
        </p>
        <h2>The mountains</h2>
        <p>
          Somewhere in there I started hiking. I didn't grow up doing it.
          The Whites are a long way from where I was raised. But once I got
          into them, the mountains became the proof — the place where
          everything I was learning about the body either worked or it
          didn't. I finished the New England 4,000-footers in 2023. I'm
          working on the Hundred Highest now, slower because the road in
          matters more than the summit.
        </p>
        <p>
          I hike with a continuous glucose monitor on the back of my arm.
          Every five minutes it tells me what's happening in real time.
          Most of what I know about training a Type 1 athlete I learned by
          being one with a graph on my arm.
        </p>
        <h2>Today</h2>
        <p>
          I coach out of a strength gym on the North Shore of Massachusetts.
          I work mostly with adults — thirty to seventy — who want to feel
          like themselves in their bodies for a long time. Some are training
          for a specific peak. Some are training so the next twenty winters
          don't take what the last twenty did. Some are managing a chronic
          condition and want a coach who's been there.
        </p>
        <p>The work is steady. I like that.</p>
        <blockquote>
          If you're going to spend the next forty years in a body, the only
          sensible thing is to learn how it works.
        </blockquote>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section style="background: var(--forest-deep); color: var(--paper);">
    <div class="container" style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 5fr 7fr; gap: 80px; align-items: start;">
      <div>
        <span class="eyebrow" style="color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--dune) 70%, transparent);">On Food</span>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper); margin-top: 14px; max-width: 14ch;">
          The kitchen is the other gym.
        </h2>
        <p style="font-family: var(--serif); font-style: italic; font-size: 20px; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--dune-soft); margin-top: 28px; max-width: 32ch;">
          A life with Type 1 Diabetes taught me to read food the way a
          navigator reads weather — closely, honestly, and with respect for
          what it actually is.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="prose" style="color: var(--dune-soft);">
        <p style="color: var(--dune-soft);">
          The CGM on my arm is the most honest teacher I've had. It doesn't
          care what a label promises. It tells me, in five-minute
          increments, what a meal actually does inside a body. After
          fifteen years of reading that graph, a few things have stayed
          true.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--dune-soft);">
          <strong style="color: var(--paper);">Eat food, mostly from people you can name.</strong>
          I cook out of a small kitchen with a heavy pan and a sharp knife.
          Most of what's in it came from a farm an hour from here, a
          butcher I've known for years, or a garden I tended myself.
          Organic where it matters; local before organic; whole before
          either. Not a religion — a default.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--dune-soft);">
          <strong style="color: var(--paper);">Cook the verb, not the noun.</strong>
          "Cooking" is a practice, not a recipe. It's onions and salt and
          the patience to let a thing brown. It's stock on a Sunday. It's
          the same six dinners on rotation in winter because they work.
          Most of what people call "eating well" is a logistics problem
          solved by being the person who cooks.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--dune-soft);">
          <strong style="color: var(--paper);">Protein is the spine of the plate.</strong>
          Then vegetables, then fat, then — if the day asked for it — a
          real, identifiable carbohydrate. Roasted potatoes. Rice.
          Sourdough from a bakery that ferments it long enough to mean
          something. The order matters. Glucose curves are gentler when
          protein and fat go first; my arm taught me that before any paper
          did.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--dune-soft);">
          <strong style="color: var(--paper);">What you don't eat is half the answer.</strong>
          Industrial seed oils. Shelf-stable bread. Anything that lists
          more than seven things on the back. I'm not interested in fear,
          and I'm not interested in purity. I'm interested in what reads
          cleanly on the graph the next morning.
        </p>
        <p style="font-family: var(--serif); font-style: italic; font-size: 19px; line-height: 1.55; color: var(--paper); border-left: 2px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--dune) 50%, transparent); padding-left: 22px; margin-top: 36px;">
          A note on scope: I'm a movement coach, not a dietitian. What's
          here is how I eat, what fifteen years of living with T1D has
          taught me, and the kind of conversation I'm happy to have with
          clients over coffee. Anything that needs a prescription pad
          belongs to a different professional, and I'll tell you so.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section style="background: var(--paper-warm);">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">Field Record</span>
      <h2 style="margin-top: 14px; max-width: 22ch;">A short list of facts.</h2>
      <div class="info-row" style="margin-top: 36px;">
        <div><dt>Certified</dt><dd>CHEK IMS L1 · HLC L1</dd></div>
        <div><dt>Coaches at</dt><dd>North Shore Strength &amp; Movement</dd></div>
        <div><dt>Diagnosis</dt><dd>T1D · 2009</dd></div>
      </div>
      <div class="info-row" style="border-top:none;">
        <div><dt>NE 4,000-footers</dt><dd>67 of 67 · finished 2023</dd></div>
        <div><dt>Hundred Highest</dt><dd>71 of 100 &amp; counting</dd></div>
        <div><dt>Home base</dt><dd>Beverly, Massachusetts</dd></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container" style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; gap: 24px;">
      <div
        class="photo-frame"
        style="aspect-ratio: 4/5; background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1500039436846-25ae2f11882e?w=900&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop')"
      >
        <div class="label">Cape Cod · Race Point</div>
      </div>
      <div
        class="photo-frame"
        style="aspect-ratio: 4/5; background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551632811-561732d1e306?w=900&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop')"
      >
        <div class="label">Mt. Madison · Northern Pres.</div>
      </div>
      <div
        class="photo-frame"
        style="aspect-ratio: 4/5; background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1571388208497-71bedc66e932?w=900&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop')"
      >
        <div class="label">Detail — CGM, summit, Sept</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container" style="text-align:center;">
      <span class="eyebrow">What's next</span>
      <h2 style="margin-top: 14px; max-width: 24ch; margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;">
        If any of this sounds like the coach you've been looking for —
      </h2>
      <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary" style="margin-top: 28px;">
        Get in touch <span class="arrow">→</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
